Here is an example of a function that sorts an array of strings in alphabetical order:
```
function sortStrings(arr) {
  return arr.sort((a, b) => a.localeCompare(b));
}
```
This function uses the `sort()` method and provides a compare function that uses the `localeCompare()` method to compare two strings. The `localeCompare()` method returns a negative value if the first string is less than the second string, a positive value if the first string is greater than the second string, and 0 if the strings are equal.

Here's an example of how you can use this function:
```
const arr = ["hello", "world", "abc", "def", "ghi"];
const sortedArr = sortStrings(arr);
console.log(sortedArr); // Output: ["abc", "def", "ghi", "hello", "world"]
```
Note that the `localeCompare()` method is case-sensitive, so uppercase letters will come before lowercase letters in the sorted array. If you want to ignore case, you can use the `toLowerCase()` or `toUpperCase()` method to convert both strings to the same case before comparing them:
```
function sortStrings(arr) {
  return arr.sort((a, b) => a.toLowerCase().localeCompare(b.toLowerCase()));
}
```
This will produce a case-insensitive sort.

